    <a title="Kbullock" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3833115-kbullock"><img alt="Kbullock" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1315084078p2/3833115.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/160047323?book_show_action=true">Apr 10, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kbullock" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kbullock" href="/user/show/3833115-kbullock">Kbullock</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer160047323" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8460594907507313906">I read this book on the recommendation of a friend who was peripherally involved in the trial proceedings. The publisher bills it as a &quot;mesmerizing page-turner,&quot; but that&apos;s only true of a few portions of it. The first chapter, a fast-moving, &quot;just the facts&quot; account of the kidnapping, is very well done. The author&apos;s description of how Italian law enforcement used cell phone traces and hotel records to identify approximately half of the operatives of the clumsy CIA operation is also interesting. </span>
  <span id="freeText8460594907507313906" style="display:none">I read this book on the recommendation of a friend who was peripherally involved in the trial proceedings. The publisher bills it as a "mesmerizing page-turner," but that's only true of a few portions of it. The first chapter, a fast-moving, "just the facts" account of the kidnapping, is very well done. The author's description of how Italian law enforcement used cell phone traces and hotel records to identify approximately half of the operatives of the clumsy CIA operation is also interesting. Finally, the account of the author's interview with Abu Omar, the subject of the CIA operation, is well done. <br /><br />Unfortunately, the rest of the book is a muddle of editorializing and meandering historical background material. The author uses the Abu Omar case as a vehicle for a polemic against CIA covert operations in general. <br /><br />The subtitle is "The CIA on Trial," but that is not a literal description of the book's contents. The author's coverage of the Italian trials of the CIA operatives is perfunctory. Hendricks would have done a much better job if he had stuck to the "just the facts" approach he used in the first chapter and allowed readers to draw their own conclusions. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8460594907507313906" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


