    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_786511694" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/786511694" />
    <a title="Sandeep Singh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21443321-sandeep-singh"><img alt="Sandeep Singh" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/786511694?book_show_action=true">Dec 10, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sandeep Singh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sandeep Singh" href="/user/show/21443321-sandeep-singh">Sandeep Singh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer786511694" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13121817868596333259"> A Kidnapping in Milan tells the story of Abu Omar, a radical imam who has been on the CIA’s wish list for his reputation in terrorism. This book is set in Milan, Italy, where CIA operatives have been monitoring the streets that Abu Omar normally uses, waiting for the perfect time to execute the mission. Wanting nothing more than to return home, Abu Omar must endure months of brutal torture to satisfy his aggressors that wish to seek information from him. He tries to survive for as long as his b</span>
  <span id="freeText13121817868596333259" style="display:none"> A Kidnapping in Milan tells the story of Abu Omar, a radical imam who has been on the CIA’s wish list for his reputation in terrorism. This book is set in Milan, Italy, where CIA operatives have been monitoring the streets that Abu Omar normally uses, waiting for the perfect time to execute the mission. Wanting nothing more than to return home, Abu Omar must endure months of brutal torture to satisfy his aggressors that wish to seek information from him. He tries to survive for as long as his body would allow while the CIA attempts to make their involvement in this atrocity unnoticeable. This book is a portrayal of the war on terror from a different perspective, which makes us question the planning of secret organizations with the intent of promoting safety and security such as the CIA.<br />	An example of these plans is the actual kidnapping. The scenario depicted in the book started with a CIA agent on his patrol about to end his shift when suddenly a car pulls up next to him demanding him to get him, also stating that he was sent by the CIA. The man in the car knows where Abu Omar will be and goes over the plan with him before dropping him off at the expected location. Surely enough Abu Omar is seen walking down the street towards him. He was instructed to set him up against the van and stall him until the passengers took him. So as Omar arrived, the CIA agent shows his identity and asked him for his identification papers making sure Omar’ s back was leaning on the van. Two minutes went by and the agent was starting to worry and began to thoroughly analyze every document he had in his hands. As soon as he was starting to lose hope the sliding door on the van was violently jerked open, the hulking men inside grabbed him, and the van sped off as the door closed, beating the helpless Abu Omar and introducing him to his new life that he would have for the next two years.<br />	Ultimately, the story of the CIA’s involvement with Abu Omar is a story of how terrorism and the justice system take action, by finding a man striving for peace through acts of terrorism, capturing, interrogating, and torturing this arrogant peacemaker, and figuring out the perpetrators behind this inhumane plan. It all adds up to the ineffectiveness of torture, a method wrongfully used to obtain information, which many secret service organizations look to as a solution. A Kidnapping in Milan tells the story very well, reminding us that while people can commit very harmful crimes, they are still human and do not deserve such horrendous treatment. <br />	This book displays this real life story descriptively and includes the details as to how he was treated; making those parts of the book seem very interesting. However, it is followed by a whole set of information afterward to provide a further insight to the topic. The book covers the story of Abu Omar’s life, and also contains details of many other terrorist organizations and a brief history of torture, from its variety to its effectiveness. Therefore, I recommend this book to anyone who seems to enjoy both aspects. I got into it just to follow along with a man’s story of survival and seeing justice served afterwards but I still managed to get through the chapters it had of additional information. <br />	This book did have obvious views that would lead to an efferent or aesthetic reading experience. I have discussed the efferent reading displayed in parts of the book such as the younger Abu Omar and the chapters dedicated to explaining torture. I learned more about torture than I had previously known which made me draw my conclusion to its ineffectiveness. Torture had been around for many years and used by many civilizations of people. One fact that I learned that seems to fit with Omar’s struggle is that prisoners sometimes admit to crimes that they didn’t commit just so they can avoid torture. This has led to many inaccurate results and it made me wonder if Abu Omar ever had to plead guilty to something he didn’t do just to avoid the beatings. This efferent reading was added on to the main story which helped me maintain a clearer aesthetic experience. <br />	The aesthetic experience was what I was after when I first picked out this book. The struggle that Abu Omar had to go through was a pretty gripping part of the book. Having to go along with his journey of dreadful treatment with descriptive details of the pain inflicted on him really grabbed my attention. It made it much more interesting once he was released from his prison and the Italian intelligence organization began cracking down on clues as to who caused this setup. This part of the book turns the genre into a mystery sort of theme as detective work is done to figure out the culprits responsible for all the suffering caused to Abu Omar, while the CIA operatives that participated in this try to lie low for as long as possible. <br /> <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13121817868596333259" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

